EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
-----------------
The guide's March 2026 update migrated the recommended model from qwen2.5:7b-instruct-q4_K_M
to qwen3:8b-q4_K_M. This migration introduced a critical regression: Qwen3's hybrid
thinking architecture is fundamentally incompatible with Open WebUI's tool-call response
pipeline as of March 2026. The result is a broken user experience for the primary use
cases this guide is designed for — memory recall, filesystem access, and notes management.

The recommendation is to revert EX.1 to qwen2.5:7b-instard-q4_K_M as the primary model
until the Open WebUI / Ollama Qwen3 tool-call pipeline is stabilised upstream, or until
a verified workaround is documented and tested.


================================================================================
ISSUE 1 — CRITICAL: Qwen3 tool-call responses silently empty in Open WebUI
================================================================================

SYMPTOM
-------
When a tool (filesystem, memory, or notes via mcpo) is invoked in Open WebUI:
- The tool call executes correctly (mcpo logs confirm 200 OK responses).
- Ollama processes the tool response correctly (logs confirm 200 OK, ~3–28 s response times).
- Open WebUI renders NOTHING after the tool result arrives. The response area shows
  a spinning indicator and then goes blank. No text. No error.

In some sessions the model enters an infinite tool-call loop, calling list_directory or
search_nodes every ~4 seconds indefinitely, never producing a final answer.

REPRODUCTION
------------
Reliably reproduced on:
  - Open WebUI :main (March 2026)
  - Ollama 0.9.x with qwen3:8b-q4_K_M
  - mcpo :main with filesystem + memory servers
  - Function Calling: Native (as required by Qwen3 architecture)
  - think (Ollama) toggle: both On and Off trigger the issue (see Issue 2)

ROOT CAUSE — CONFIRMED BY UPSTREAM ISSUES
------------------------------------------
This is a known, actively reported bug across multiple Open WebUI GitHub issues:

  [open-webui/open-webui #14577] "Tool calling BROKEN" (June 2025)
  — Qwen3:30b-a3b calls tool, makes the tool call, but never answers.
  Confirmed on Ollama 0.9.0 + Open WebUI v0.6.13 with mcpo + native tool calling.

  [open-webui/open-webui #15346] "Error parsing tool call arguments" (June 2025)
  — Qwen3:4b + Open WebUI native tool calling causes argument parse errors:
    "Error parsing tool call arguments: {...}{...} - {}"
  The model concatenates multiple JSON objects without a separator, breaking
  Open WebUI's parser.

  [open-webui/open-webui #15546] "OWUI cannot parse tool call parameters when LLM
  makes multiple tool calls at once" (July 2025)
  — Confirmed on Qwen3:8b-q4_K_M and Qwen3:14b. Raw API response shows <think>
  tokens interleaved with tool call JSON, which Open WebUI cannot parse correctly.
  Quote from thread: "Local models are not reliable for tool calling especially at
  <14b size." The issue persists even at 14b+ for Qwen3.

  [open-webui/open-webui #17135] "sending malformed role:tool messages" (Sept 2025)
  — Open WebUI sends `"content": null` in tool role messages, which is non-compliant
  with the OpenAI schema. This causes downstream LLMs (including Qwen3) to receive
  a malformed tool result and either loop or produce empty responses.

ADDITIONAL FACTOR: think (Ollama) toggle interaction
- When think=Off: Qwen3 generates zero content tokens after receiving a tool result.
  The model appears to require thinking tokens to reason about tool responses before
  producing output. Disabling think suppresses this internal chain and leaves the
  model with no pathway to generate a final answer.
- When think=On (Default): Qwen3 runs the full reasoning trace (~36 seconds observed)
  then also produces empty final content. Open WebUI's reasoning tag parser intercepts
  the <think>...</think> block and then finds nothing left to render.

Both states are broken. This is not a configuration issue — it is a fundamental
incompatibility between Qwen3's hybrid thinking architecture and Open WebUI's current
tool-call pipeline.

PARAMETER think=false — NOT AVAILABLE IN MODELFILE
---------------------------------------------------
The guide instructs using PARAMETER think false in the Modelfile to disable thinking.
This parameter does NOT exist in Ollama's Modelfile spec as of March 2026:

  $ docker exec ollama ollama create wall-e -f /tmp/Wall-E.modelfile
  Error: unknown parameter 'think'

The think field is only available as a per-request API parameter (not a Modelfile
PARAMETER). It cannot be baked into a custom model definition. The /no_think system
prompt token is the only Modelfile-level approach, but it is insufficient to prevent
Open WebUI from sending think=true in its API requests, which overrides the system
prompt token for Qwen3's thinking mode.


================================================================================
ISSUE 2 — MODERATE: PARAMETER think false does not exist in Ollama Modelfile spec
================================================================================

SYMPTOM
-------
EX.1 Step 4 instructs adding "PARAMETER think false" to the Wall-E Modelfile.
This causes ollama create to fail with "Error: unknown parameter 'think'".

ROOT CAUSE
----------
The think field is an API-level parameter per Ollama's official documentation
(https://docs.ollama.com/capabilities/thinking), not a Modelfile PARAMETER.
Supported Modelfile PARAMETERs are: num_ctx, temperature, top_p, top_k,
repeat_penalty, stop, seed, num_predict, and a small number of others.
"think" is not in this list.

IMPACT
------
Any user who follows the guide update and attempts to add PARAMETER think false
will get a hard error and be unable to build the wall-e model at all until they
manually remove the line.

RECOMMENDATION
--------------
Remove PARAMETER think false from the Modelfile example entirely.
The /no_think system prompt token (already in the guide's SYSTEM block) is the
correct Modelfile-level approach. Document that Open WebUI may override this via
its own think (Ollama) toggle, which must be set to Default (not Off) in the model's
Advanced Parameters to avoid the empty-response regression.


================================================================================
ISSUE 3 — MODERATE: Qwen3 infinite tool-call loop behaviour
================================================================================

SYMPTOM
-------
When thinking mode is active (think=Default or On), and the model is asked a question
requiring tool recall (e.g. "List files in /nc-data"), the model enters a loop:
- Calls list_directory → receives result → calls list_directory again → repeat.
- Loop runs until the user manually stops the generation.
- mcpo logs confirm the tool is called every ~4 seconds indefinitely.
- Ollama returns 200 OK for every call — the issue is in the model's post-tool reasoning.

ROOT CAUSE
----------
With thinking mode active, Qwen3 8b treats each tool result as insufficient and
re-invokes the tool to "verify". This is a known behaviour of smaller Qwen3 variants
(<14b) when thinking mode is enabled alongside tool calling. The model's chain-of-thought
reasoning loop does not converge when tool results are short or list-like.

RECOMMENDATION
--------------
Document the loop risk for Qwen3 8b + thinking mode + mcpo. Until upstream is fixed,
add an Open WebUI setting note: Settings → Interface → "Tool Call Auto-Execute Max
Count" → set to 5. This caps loop depth even if it does not fix the underlying issue.


================================================================================
ISSUE 4 — INFORMATIONAL: Open WebUI built-in Memory conflicts with mcpo memory tool
================================================================================

SYMPTOM
-------
Open WebUI has its own built-in "Memory" capability (visible under model settings →
Builtin Tools). When both the built-in Memory and the mcpo memory tool server are
active simultaneously, the model receives duplicate memory tool definitions and may
call the wrong one or become confused about which to use.

RECOMMENDATION
--------------
Add a note in EX.2 (Open WebUI initial setup) to disable the built-in Memory builtin
tool for the wall-e model:
  Open WebUI → Workspace → Models → wall-e → (edit) → Builtin Tools → Memory: OFF
The mcpo memory tool (graph.json knowledge graph) is the persistent, cross-restart
memory store. The built-in Open WebUI memory is session-scoped and separate.


